tip.text:
This gem of a cafe is a welcome addition to Hackney serving up delicious coffee blends in a minimal and airy space adorned with retro stylings. It's just the kind of cafe you'd expect to find in such ends: calm, white walls, full of people doing things on their laptops that are innumerably more important than whatever you are doing on yours.

They pride themselves on their coffee here, so kick things off with a cup of joe, while you decide whether their brunch menu is tempting enough to hang around for. Sourdough bread, slow-roast beans, fried mushrooms and prosciutto topped with poached eggs sure worked on us.

That vegan cafe in Bethnal Green everyone is raving about. You've heard of it. We're sure you have. It's 100% vegan, community run and not for profit. Get your vegan samosas, sausage rolls, cakes and milkshakes, or go for a posh coffee.

You can also buy produce to take away, including vegan cheeses, faux meats, tofu, tempeh, Club Mate & Fritz Kola (German drinks), as well as politically-charged vegan cookbooks. Because you never know when you might need one. Hell, you could probably use one right now.

To all those who think vegans don't do it indulgent we present: We Are Vegan Everything. A very Insta friendly, Bali-vibes brunch spot and cafe in Hackney that's doing mighty, naughty things with plant-based food. We came in for brunch and were really damn satisfied by both the sweet (blueberry pancakes and vegan coconut cream) and savoury (sourdough topped with tomatoes, mushrooms and avocado). It feels like the kind of place an Australian wellness influencer in Bali would have created, and we mean that in a nice way. The freakshake, meanwhile, is one of the most rich and decadent shakes we've ever sampled.

If you’re wondering if this Breaking Bad-themed cocktail bar is all gimmick, we should say: it is. But it has enough attention to detail, enough interactivity, and enough cool shit going on that it transcends what could just exist as a clickbait FB video and becomes a place that we might actually recommend. The whole thing is built into an RV truck like the one from the show; you’ll don yellow safety suits, grab a welcome cocktail of crystal meth (a mojito in a flask with a syringe of blue liquid) and take a seat somewhere in the meth lab caravan. The menu takes you straight back to your GCSEs with Bunsen burners, test tubes, and neon-coloured alcoholic beverages.

The cocktails are a little sweet for our tastes but the fun here is the spectacle: using dry ice to create vanilla smoke to infuse our peach liquor with; using syringes and an electric pump to make white chocolate foam; and best/weirdest of all - a bowl of Kahlúa-milk Rice Crispies. It’s an experience, and for £35 quid for two hours and three cocktails, is just inside the realms of not a bump.

Outside of the RV they’ve got another bar, vegan pizzas, a pumping hip hop soundtrack, and arcade machines where you’ll be awarded a shot depending on your score. Oh, and the whole place is vegan. Seriously there’s a lot going on at this place, and we’re still trying to wrap our heads around it all. Or maybe we actually just took meth and this was all some fever-dream. Is anyone else itchy?

This quaint little cafe is not geographically constrained by its Hackney location, and serves up some top notch platters focussing on cuisines from all over. From Latino, Scandinavian, Oriental, Middle Eastern, American... it's pretty much got it all. Oh, and they're all only £7.50. Despite the worldly dishes, they've still got that Hackney community vibe, with convivial seating, regular supper clubs and local artwork plastered on the walls.

If you only feel peckish, the tea here is pretty fuckin' delightful, served in cute tea-sets, pots and saucers, all sourced from local junk shops. Service can be a tad slow, but it's more because they're overwhelmed, and not because they're rude and cba, so we feel mean for even bringing it up.

Imagine if Wes Anderson and Marie Antoinette had a love child, and that love child had a popular lifestyle blog in Palm Springs and was Instagram famous. That's the general vibe at Palm Vault, Hackney's (and we'd be willing to bet the world's) most aesthetically pleasing cafe.

With low hanging plants suspended from the ceiling, exposed brick, and a pastel colour scheme that puts Ladurée to shame, the atmosphere here will have you seeing la vie en rose. Oh, and the food is pretty great too, concentrating on locally-sourced plant based dishes that have inspired songs in the hearts of the Hackney vegan community. A must-try (for the 'gram as much as for the taste) is their fuchsia-hued velvet latte, which is made from beetroot and steamed milk (your choice from an extensive list of vegan substitutes). We also loved the avocado chocolate cake, and will never stop being mesmerised by the colour-changing "Magick Tea" which is nothing short of sorcery.

listing.name: Dark Arts Coffee / I Will Kill Again
listing.subtitle: Roastery and Cafe

tip.text:
Some sort of enigmatic magic is afoot in a railway arch in Homerton, where an alluring mishmash of the occult, biker culture and insanely good coffee is turning people a little bit crazy - although it could just be that jitter juice. A roastery during the week (Dark Arts Coffee); a vegan-orientated cafe on the weekends (I Will Kill Again), we rate this as a really memorable place to do the coffee and brunch thing in East.

The coffee is dangerously moreish: beans from all over the world that are uniquely blended into something so damn creamy you can almost taste the threat of your own demise. The brunch, meanwhile, is of the quality to have vegans and non-vegans alike rushing down to get into plates that artfully combine smoked tempeh rashers, crispy potato rosti and sweet sun-dried tomatoes to create something greater than the sum of their parts. Throw in a chilled ambience with laid-back, black-clad owners dripping with cool, and you have yourself a spot that walks the walk and talks the talk.

Chicken shops are a dime a dozen in London, but there's one newcomer that's cornered a fresh angle - House of Hackney (used to be called House of Seitan), with their vegan fried chicken and classic chip shop sides, completely blew up social media as they opened their doors for hoards of hungry herbivores.

Cheekily situated next to a butcher's shop (and with queues that put that butcher's shop to shame), the Seitan "chicken" lives up to the real thing, albeit much more bird friendly (and a little pricier) than your OG chicken and chips. Whether you're a flexitarian, participating in Veganuary, or stay meat-free year round, it's nice to know that you can now indulge in your favourite comfort food without compromising your morals.

We lament the fall of the tram as much as the next app, but that cloud has a silver lining because the old Clapton Tram Depot has been superbly converted into a soothing, beautiful café full of botany, exposed brickwork, ancient beams and parquetry flooring. The owners of this place have really put some time into the aesthetic and we're digging it. They serve breakfast, lunch and also sell a range of organic products from this light-filled space.

Whilst the lunch menu features a couple of toasted sandwiches and a soup of the day, we stopped by for a lazy breakfast where the menu comes with all the classics: Bloody Mary, sourdough, granola, eggs, bacon. Whatever you do, though, get a dish featuring their portobello mushrooms in tarragon and soya cashew cream - you won't regret it. With soft piano music playing overhead, and locals reading the paper and having a chat, this is a green oasis of calm in Clapton.

You might walk past Lardo in London Fields thinking it was just another posh warehouse conversion, but once you spot the glimmering disco ball-like pizza oven hanging from the ceiling, you'll know this is a chiller affair. You'll also know it's Lardo, as there's no signage on the door.

There's a lovely outdoor area if you're there on the one night of the year where it's warm enough to sit outside, or plenty of seating and natural light indoors so you can see that warm, sizzling pizza. They also do pasta and all your classic Italian puds (tiramisu, you know we love you), but we'd recommend starting off the night with a cold Spritz and a charcuterie board. Because, why on earth wouldn't you?

Little bro to Hackney's Lardo, this Italian stalwart likes to stick to pasta, pizza, and la dolce vita.
Essentially named ‘baby pig fat,’ after its older sibling, Lardo Bebe isn’t as vegeterrible as it may immediately seem, with plenty of pumpkin, aubergine, kale and porcini on offer. Just sit back on their comfy cushions and enjoy the communal setting, with a glass of vino and a prosciutto cotto, artichoke, mushroom, olive and tomato 'za. Top that off with a tiramisu, and your date will be all over you.

OK we've seen the look on your face. How can a pub be 100% vegan, you're wondering. Well it pretty much means that, wherever possible, all the trimmings (food, drinks, fixtures and fittings) are plant-based and sustainably sourced.

Food is seen to by Club Mexicana which means tacos, nachos and burritos piled high with guacamole, tomatillo salsa, sour cream, pink onions, pickled chillies, chimichurri, fresh lime and coriander. Sounds tingly and tasty right? Our fave was the tofish sandwich which went down a treat. Wash all that down with cask ales (without the fish bits), Beavertown beer, small batch wines and some tasty cocky Ts.

We also popped by for brunch and devoured some tangy, spicy chick'n waffles with chilli maple and bacon (as decadent as it sounds); a full Mexican breakfast with all the plant-based trimmings; some fried tortillas with cherries and cream; and more cocktails that we'd care to admit. It's very on trend, for sure, but it's got the flavour chops to back itself.

Kitchen closed on Mondays.

No way are the vegan wizards behind The Brook about to sacrifice flavour in their pursuit of plant-based pleasure - this is as close to vegan junk food as we've found in London. It's a vegan tapas restaurant and cocktail bar; a suitably laid-back, friendly and DIY-chic space where vegans and curious non-vegans enter the doors to see what's next in the vegolution. The answer: pretty nice grub with a surprising and satisfying indulgence about it.

The tip is to share five or six of their tapas dishes between two - and let us point you towards the moreish sesame chick'n skewers; the bountiful and comforting jackfruit quesadillas; and a zingy lime and coconut dal. Portion sizes are not huge - and potentially a pound or two over what we'd like - but given the meticulous R&D and care gone into creating each dish, we're prepared to make allowances.

The cocktails here are also not a simple add-on. Their huge choice of converted classics and house specials are put on the same footing as the food - meaning that whilst hungry foodies frequent the front and tuck into the tasty bits, the bar area and tables at the back create an altogether looser vibe.

This is one of those haunts where brunch can accidentally slide into lunch, and maybe even blend into dinner - so wear your stretchy pants. Autumn Yard is an all-day eatery serving up lip-spankingly good dishes, we're talking smokey cannellini stew, piled high on garlic-smothered sourdough; salmon teriyaki on a stack of butternut squash and black puy lentils; and crispy pulled lamb with orange carrot mash.

The food is paired with an equally lovely ambience. The airy warehouse is decked out with long communal tables, dark furnishings and an open plan kitchen - whilst an outdoor terrace sees revellers sprawled across benches, enjoying a beer or two.

Owned by the enigmatic King Cook, this London Fields spot is a favourite of grime outfit Boy Better Know with JME a regular fixture. King Cook's taken a millennial approach to veganism, with no preachy, dreadlocked “crusties” on site and a menu perfect for meat eaters and vegans alike. There's a dish called High Grade - a bowl of hemp oil stir-fried veggies in sweet and sour BBQ sauce, topped with green herbs and hemp seed crumbles - which should tell you all you need to know.

The menu is mostly taken up by creamy Thai curries and gingery noodle dishes, with a few nods to multicultural London: there's a tofu scramble full English, a few Jamaican goodies, a Yoga Fire (turmeric dahl), and a provencal garlicky, herby, truffle oil number too. Further up the scale of healthiness than a lot of East London vegan fast-food spots, a lot more delish' and with 100% more street cred; we've got a lotta time for Cook Daily.

For a place with so much footfall, the selection of eateries on Broadway Market is surprisingly not all that. Baba Souks, however, is a relaxing and welcoming cafe well worth an excursion to. Stepping through the door here you'll be greeted with a welcoming smile, Arabian rugs, a pleasing amount of terracotta and greenery and a melodic Middle Eastern soundtrack. London Fields becomes languid Tel Aviv.

It's almost always a relaxed vibe here where you're grabbing coffee, brunch, a takeaway lunchtime wrap or an evening shared platter featuring all that good, reliable, Middle Eastern produce. The Baba sharing platter, coming it at a just about reasonable £20, was a hearty and healthy-tasting combination of flavours with poached eggs, halloumi, falafel, hummus, moutabel, and a couple of things we couldn’t immediately identify. Ask no questions, just dip your sourdough or crudité in and munch on those trustworthy, dependable flavours.

With its black facade, super-dim lighting and low-key rustic wooden decor, Hackney Bureau is just the kind of place you might stroll right past on your daily quest for something delicious. Thankfully, you have us in your pocket, ready to guide you to a cosy bistro that focuses on high quality ingredients and serving up brunch, lunch and dinner based on what's fresh.

At various times of the day you'll find people reading the Guardian, gossiping over coffee or simmering down over supper. It's a popular joint alright, and liable to get rammo in the evening or at weekend brunch time. The dinner menu changes often but features dishes such as spaghetti with clams, marinated rump of lamb and pan-fried sea bass. Good eating, super moody, and a date-night staple.

We're buzzing for this healthy eatery, dishing out vegetarian food, cold pressed juices, coffee, wine, cocktails, and craft beer to health-conscious diners who also like to let their hair down. Breakfast is quite wholesome, featuring all the usual suspects (muesli, acai bowl, avo toast); come lunchtime, we recommend the scrumptious Hive Burger - made with a mushroom, courgette and pumpkin seed patty with homemade mayo.

The evening is an altogether more elevated affair, featuring aperitivo and drinks. The cocktails are quality, but it's the wines that are the real star here - all of which are natural and expertly curated. Try the light and crisp Salvetta Nosiola, a white wine from Trentino that's only offered by the Hive in the city. On Tuesdays, they do 2-for-1 craft beers between 6 and 9pm. Look out for their wine tasting nights, as well. Overall, a good spot to indulge without feeling indulgent.

If you're angling for an Americano, keep on walking. Tea is the daddy at Tiosk - in all its glorious loose-leaf glory - and by George is it a beauty. There's a brew for everyone here, and even a macha latte for the coffee fiends crossing over to the tea side gradually.

On the grub side, this is a vegan and gluten-free paradise, with goodies like gingered black bean stew going on. This is definitely a Broadway Market winner, especially if you're in need of a cleansing breakfast.

Do you sometimes wish you were Rick Stein on a culinary tour of the Mediterranean coast? Well you're not. But here's the next best thing: a charming bistro at the bottom of Broadway Market that seems to take all the best flavours from Spain, Italy, Greece and Turkey and compile them on one manageable, delicious menu.

It's an ambient spot, filled with overhanging greenery, gentle lighting and a soundtrack that occasionally drifts into Euro-pop. Like being on holiday somewhere sunny, but with nice food. Here are some things you absolutely must eat: the Picos blue and date croquetas; the octopus with hummus and cumin yoghurt; and the free range chicken thigh with honey poached apricots, sumac yoghurt and pistachios. And then end things with a deconstructed baklava with almonds, whipped cream and mango. 'Glorious' you say to yourself, as the camera pans out to reveal Regent's Canal.
